tice that the clear method sets the position to 0 and the limit to capacity. After a read operation, the limit changes based on bytes read, but the position stays at 0. This is because the read function uses the array, not the position. If I add the runtime, compiling and running the Java test might pass, but I'm still evaluating if native should include it. The user has instructed not to run, so I need to focus on editing the build.gradle instead.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_HlBJn23Bupv3OXJsZiU1lMes|fc_023c2f98684b946e0169fe5ca291d88194bcbe9e9517600916", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.apache.orc/orc-shims/1.7.8/build.gradle", "edits": [{"oldText": "    testImplementation \"org.apache.orc:orc-shims:$libraryVersion\"\n    testImplementation 'org.apache.hadoop:hadoop-client-api:3.3.4'\n    testImplementation 'org.assertj:assertj-core:3.22.0'\n}", "newText": "    testImplementation \"org.apache.orc:orc-shims:$libraryVersion\"\n    testImplementation 'org.apache.hadoop:hadoop-client-api:3.3.4'\n    testImplementation 'org.apache.hadoop:hadoop-client-runtime:3.3.4'\n    testImplementation 'org.assertj:assertj-core:3.22.0'\n}"}]}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 3314, "output": 1729, "cacheRead": 54272, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 59315, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778277512146, "responseId": "resp_023c2f98684b946e0169fe5c88f1888194b1e71cf97b7ae6b4"}}
